On my channel I review the @tolos Archetype 1.0’s, and this should answer the question of “what are the best flat shoes for powerlifting?” Everyone will have their preference, but these are currently my top pick.

These are a cheaper alternative to the Vivo Primus Lite III’s, but with just as much quality.

The more time I spend powerlifting, the less total equipment I try to use. I’m at a point where I’d rather not have three separate pairs of shoes for all three disciplines; these shoes solved that problem.

If you enjoy the video please consider subscribing to the channel! I’m trying to produce at least two pieces of long-form content per week, including reviews, controversial topics in powerlifting, and my own training footage. Thanks!

I turn 30 today.

I’m not huge on celebrating my birthday or really anything involving myself. There’s no specific reason or anything, I’ve just always been like that. This might be the one time I’ll post for my birthday for the next few years, mainly because my life finally feels like it’s at a positive turning point.

The last couple years have been pretty difficult, but I’ve never been vocal about it because social media is this weird space where vulnerability and honesty are sort of frowned upon especially in powerlifting. You’d expect with owning a gym it would be the absolute best thing in the world for someone who’s made fitness their identity, but it just hasn’t been that for me. At least not yet.

I’m forever grateful for everyone who’s helped make Gameday what it is today, but there are more times than I’d like to admit that I don’t even like walking in there simply because I’m not able to enjoy it. I’m always looking for what can be improved, what needs to be fixed, what our members are saying, and it just leads to me feeling defeated because I always end up putting these things before myself. That on top of still working a corporate job at the time and trying to train had me in a very poor state of mind but I couldn’t show that to anyone. It’s not so much that I had to remain stoic, but letting these thoughts out and moping around wouldn’t do anyone any good. Most of 28 and 29 was a facade, but my team kept my head on straight and I couldn’t be more thankful to have them (@nicoflores83kg @joe_gameday @avataraangdrew @kennykdao @kg.lifts.kgs).

I have a good feeling about 30, though. I started a new job at @raskolapparel as the Head of U.S. Fulfillment and Logistics (@omarisuf BIG HOSS) and I’m actually in a place where I can make powerlifting and competing a priority again. There will still be plenty of low points, but I think the hard part is finally over and I can breathe.

Our weightlifting platforms needed some desperate reinforcement, so another layer of plywood was added to make things sturdier and more even. The next step of this process will be making adjustments to the stall mats, but that will be at a later date. For now all nine platforms are much sturdier!

In Strength and Skill

If you own any equipment that’s used for working out, make sure you always take care of it even if it’s something as simple as a barbell. A little TLC goes a very long way!

One of the main reasons behind Gameday Barbell’s existence is to help grow the sport of powerlifting. By putting the equipment that’s used in competition in the hands of our members and visitors, we hope we’re slowly working towards that goal! If you want to practice how you compete, make sure to stop by.

Maybe he’s born with it. Maybe it’s Raskol.

As you may know I was recently given an opportunity by Omar to help grow @raskolapparel by taking over the US fulfillment and logistics. We recently moved into our very own warehouse to scale things further, and the whole transition from Gameday’s distribution room to the new Raskol HQ was documented on my YouTube channel (direct link in my profile bio).

The OG’s know this, but Omar was one of the very few, if not the first, people who inspired me to start making YouTube videos back in 2013. The inconsistent uploads over the years (for one reason or another, mostly lack of time) have been extremely frustrating since I love creating fitness/powerlifting content, but it seems to have paid off. If you see more videos from me, you owe it to Omar. Time is precious and I’m extremely grateful to have some of it back.

They say never meet your heroes, but this is an exception.

On this episode of what gym owners should be doing: take care of your machines!

Let’s face it, we’ve all been to gyms where the cables on some machines are snapped up and the owners either refuse or frankly just forget to make repairs. Our seated cable row was out of commission for a few weeks but now has a new cable that’s ready for use!

These cables are extremely durable but get worn down the most when weights are slammed at the end of a set. Please remember to be a little more gentle and these cables will last much longer!

Yesterday I sat down exactly eight years after competing in my very first powerlifting meet to say that I am actually going to be taking a step back from powerlifting as a competitor. It’s been pretty clear the last two years my heart wasn’t in it anymore, and I was sort of just delaying the inevitable.

I’m still going to be active in the community because the sport has provided me with so much and I wish to continue seeing it grow, even if my contribution helps only a small amount. I simply miss having fun with training and want a new challenge that I have zero expectations of.

Weightlifting, mobility, athleticism, and losing unwanted body fat. Those are the fitness-related goals right now. If people want to take this as me turning my back on the sport or giving up because I’m not getting stronger, that’s fine. I don’t need a final competition to show that I’m closing this chapter of my life, especially since I’m going to continue giving to the sport that’s given me so much.

If I ever influenced you to start powerlifting and you continue to love it to this day, stick to it. My experience with the sport does not have to be yours.

Started the @dozer.wl Re-Entry Program earlier in the week since I’m transitioning back to weightlifting from powerlifting. There’s a bunch of differences between the two disciplines, but the biggest thing for me right now is the mobility demand.

LIFT ANALYSIS

Just wrapped up Week 2 of the @dozer.wl Re-Entry Program yesterday. One more week to go, but wanted to change content up a bit with an analysis of my C&J.

I’m still figuring things out so don’t sue me, but there’s three particular components of this movement that always gave me trouble.

Bar Distance Relative to Body
When first learning the Clean I always had trouble keeping the bar close. It’s not so much the bar would drift away from me, rather my hips would drift away from the bar. This forces anyone to meet the bar with significantly more aggression, which can shoot it out in front and then force the lifter to jump forward for the catch. I’ve pretty much broken that habit and now the bar travels much straighter. Still some tweaks, but better than when I first started.

Jerk Grip Width
Because of my longer arms I’m pretty certain my jerk grip should be a tad wider than most, but again this is something I need to play around with. The wider grip demands more mobility that I’m still working for, but the reduction in ROM feels a lot better on my shoulders.

Front Foot Landing First
It’s as simple as that, I just need to do some drills to get in the habit of having my back foot land first. It’s better than the tightroping I used to do 🤷🏻‍♂️

I’m not here to argue the effectiveness of equipment, but how much more can raw lifting equipment be pushed? The last few years powerlifting has seen a massive influx of participants, whether it be for recreation or competition. With that came the rise of equipment manufacturers (or at least their visibility) geared towards powerlifters.

SBD, Stoic, A7, Inzer, Titan, Pioneer just to name a few of the more reputable brands.

What’s going to happen once belts and sleeves hit their limit in terms of innovation (if they haven’t already)? It reaches a point where lifters need to accept that the equipment does not make them or their lifts.

Again, equipment helps. That’s pretty clear and I don’t think anyone is dumb enough to argue otherwise.

What are your thoughts on this? Do you think the IWF made the right call introducing this third “Open” Category in an attempt to be more inclusive and fair? Do other sports need to adopt similar rules or does further research and analysis need to be done before making any rule changes (if you believe any are necessary)?

I feel no one will ever truly be happy with any rules or criteria introduced, but at the very least efforts are being put towards continuing the conversation.

YOU ARE WASTING YOUR MONEY ON COACHING

…if you’re not utilizing every part of the service. You and your coach entered into an agreement to make you a better lifter, so make sure you’re doing your job as an athlete so they can properly do their job as your coach. If you’re paying someone for programming, follow it. If you hired a nutritionist, hit your macros to the T. These might seem like small things but a bunch of small things over time make a huge impact.

My question to coaches: are there usually better than average results with your athletes when they’re doing what is asked of them?

If you’re planning on starting a gym, be prepared to familiarize yourself with Home Depot. You think all those trips as a kid prepared you to embark on this journey towards becoming a handyman? THINK AGAIN

In all seriousness, try doing as much renovation on your own as you can. The trios might be unbearable but you’re going to save thousands in labor costs. Maybe at the cost of your sanity, but you’re going to lose that anyway.

There’s going to be a major lifestyle shift when you open a business, and with that will come a ton of stress. It’s unavoidable. However, you get to dictate how you let that stress affects your day-to-day life.

While opening Gameday Barbell I let stress get the better of me and it still affects my life today. My diet got pretty terrible, the lack of sleep affected my mood, and I acted pretty horribly towards people I consider close.

Your diet is a pretty simple thing to address. When you have time (it’s limited) try your best to meal prep. I haven’t met one person that genuinely enjoys doing it but it’s necessary if you consider your nutrition important.

Losing sleep is unavoidable, but the quality can be adjusted.

The most important is how you act towards everyone. We all have moments where we allow stress to be the determinant of a poor attitude, but you can control that. Even if you need someone checking you whenever it happens, learning to manage your emotions when under pressure is crucial.

Stress comes with the territory. It’s your job to adapt.

I can’t even express how important it is to make time for working out while you’re building a gym. Your day is already going to be filled with renovations, moving equipment, and a bunch of other random things. The least you can do is spend an hour of your morning training. It’s very easy to use work as an excuse not to train, but the more you do that the more likely you are to stop training as a whole.
Prepare to learn things you’re probably going to ever need once or twice in your life. If anyone ever needs a scissor lift operator, I’m your guy. Just make sure there’s no painting involved.

If you thought building powerlifting platforms was hard, there’s still hope for you. Keep in mind these are NOT competition standard only because of the thickness of the wood sheets being used, but you’ll be saving over $100. The function is the exact same as a competition platform.

Materials Needed:
4x8 19/32 OSB Sheathing ($30-35 Cheaper per Sheet than Plywood)
12x8.5’ Textured Carpet (Viking Stingray from Home Depot)
1” Wood Screws
2” Wood Screws
21” 2x4 Stud
Heavy Duty Staples

Tools Needed:
Hand Drill
Staple Gun
Utility Knife
Phillips Drill Bit
5/8” Counter Sink

🔹 Counter sink wherever you’ll be drilling the layers together (two sheets)
🔹 Lay untouched sheets down, place counter sunk sheets on top rotated 90 degrees
🔹 Bind one sheet at a time, take your time
🔹 Cut carpet to 8.5 x 8.5’ and place upside down
🔹 Flip platform and place centered on carpet
🔹 Cut corners to fold each side over, staple one side at a time, trim excess carpet off and staple anything loose
🔹 Cover 2x4 in extra carpet and fasten 2” away from the front of the platform
🔹 Profit

This method is actually cheaper than making a platform out of stall mats as well, with the exception being it’s probably not best to deadlift on these. Since the wood is cheaper it’s not a big deal to replace them, but it’s recommended these are only used for combo racks. It’s always best to practice how you compete!

It rarely happens, but do you think bars outside of what are used in higher level competitions (20kg OPB, Eleiko Powerlifting Competition Bar, now 20kg @texasstrengthsystems bar, etc.) should be allowed for use?

As the rule currently stands, as long as the bar (20kg being referenced) meets the following specs it can be used for competition:

- Does not exceed 2.2mm in total length
- Distance between collar faces is not to exceed 1.32mm or be less than 1.31mm
- (LOCAL MEETS) The diameter of the bar is not to exceed 29mm or be less than 28mm
- Diameter of the sleeves are not to exceed 52mm or be less than 50mm
- Distance between rings must be 81cm
- The center knurling is not to exceed 160mm or be less than 100mm

My issue, and I’m sure others share the same sentiment, is with the original Texas Power Bar. The 28.5mm bar diameter in combination with the wide collar faces have been known throw lifters off during local meets. By no means is it a bad bar, but why allow it for use in the first place?

I think at the very least there should be criteria in place for the collar width or loadable sleeve length to keep things more consistent from meet to meet. It’s not likely to happen, but unexpected bar whip could lead to injuries.
